{{Infobox power station | name = Lalamilo Wells | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Hawaii | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= | location_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|19|59|15|N|155|45|56|W|type:landmark_dim:20km_region:US-HI|display=inline,title}} | country = United States | location = [[South Kohala, Hawaii|South Kohala]], [[Hawaii County, Hawaii]] | status = D | construction_began = | commissioned = {{start date|1985}} | decommissioned = {{end date|2010}} | cost = | owner = Hawaiian Electric Company | operator = <!------------------------- WIND FARMS --> | wind_farm_type = Onshore | wind_site_elevation = {{Convert|1273|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} | wind_site_usage = Pasture | wind_site_area = {{Convert|0.2|mi2|km2|0|abbr=on}} | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance= | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = <!------------------------- GENERAL --> | th_fuel_primary = | th_fuel_secondary = | th_fuel_tertiary = | ps_units_operational= 0 | ps_units_manu_model = Jacobs | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_decommissioned= 120 | ps_electrical_capacity= | ps_electrical_cap_fac= | ps_annual_generation= | th_cogeneration = | th_combined_cycle = | website = | extra = }} '''Lalamilo Wells''' is a wind farm on the [[Hawaii (island)|island of Hawaii]]. It is located within the ''[[ahupuaa|ahupua{{okina}}a]]'' (ancient land division) called Lalamilo,<ref>{{gnis|361706|Lalamilo}}</ref> between the coastal area known as [[Puako, Hawaii]], and the inland towns of [[Waimea, Hawaii County, Hawaii|Waimea]] and [[Waikoloa Village, Hawaii]]. It was commissioned in 1985 with 39 17.5&nbsp;kW [[Jacobs Wind|Jacobs]] wind turbines and 81 20&nbsp;kW Jacobs wind turbines, yielding a total capacity of 2.3 MW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hawaii.gov/dbedt/ert/wwg/history.html |title=History of Wind Energy Projects in Hawaii |website=State of Hawaii Department of Business, Economic Development, and Tourism |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104456/http://hawaii.gov/dbedt/ert/wwg/history.html |archivedate=June 15, 2011 |accessdate=22 January 2009 |deadurl=unfit }}</ref>
Starting in January 2006, the electric utility operating the wind farm, [[Hawaiian Electric Company]] (HELCO), operated a demonstration model of a grid-stabilizing unit, known as an Electronic Shock Absorber (ESA). This unit was designed to increase the stability of the island's grid, which has a relatively high penetration of wind energy, which is subject to rapid fluctuations.<ref>[http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/jun06/3544 IEEE Spectrum: Taking Wind Mainstream]</ref> However, the unit was damaged in an [[2006 Kiholo Bay earthquake|earthquake in October 2006]].<ref>[http://www.heco.com/portal/site/heco/menuitem.508576f78baa14340b4c0610c510b1ca/?vgnextoid=94600420af0db110VgnVCM1000005c011bacRCRD&vgnextchannel=ab020420af0db110VgnVCM1000005c011bacRCRD&vgnextfmt=defau&vgnextrefresh=1&level=0&ct=article HECO > Energy Storage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711161653/http://www.heco.com/portal/site/heco/menuitem.508576f78baa14340b4c0610c510b1ca/?vgnextoid=94600420af0db110VgnVCM1000005c011bacRCRD&vgnextchannel=ab020420af0db110VgnVCM1000005c011bacRCRD&vgnextfmt=defau&vgnextrefresh=1&level=0&ct=article |date=2011-07-11 }}</ref>
==Repowering== By 2010 the turbines were antiquated; only two-thirds were still in operation. The farm was decommissioned that year in anticipation of replacing the turbines with more efficient modern models.
Lalamilo Wind Company was awarded the contract to repower and operate the wind farm. They plan to install five Vestas V47/660&nbsp;kW turbines that together would have a generating capacity of 3.3 MW. Commercial operation is intended to begin in late 2015 or early 2016.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Windmills We Have Known and Loved |url=http://www.hawaiianelectric.com/vcmcontent/EnergyServices/Powerlines/Fall_Winter2010%5b1%5d.pdf |format=PDF |journal=Powerlines |publisher=Hawaiian Electric Company |date=2010 |issue=3 |page=9 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Yager |first1=Bret |date=26 June 2014 |title=County Plans Wind Farm to Power Water Wells |url=http://westhawaiitoday.com/news/local-news/county-plans-wind-farm-power-water-wells |newspaper=West Hawaii Today |location=Kailua-Kona, Hawaii |publisher=Oahu Publications |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stewart |first1=Colin |date=11 July 2014 |title=South Kohala Wind Farm Could Restart |url=http://hawaiitribune-herald.com/news/local-news/south-kohala-wind-farm-could-restart |newspaper=Tribune-Herald |location=Hilo, Hawaii |publisher=Oahu Publications |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>
