{{Infobox street | name =Saint Paul Street | native_name ={{lang-fr|Rue Saint-Paul}} | marker_image = | image =Pulling forward.jpg | caption =Saint Paul Street in [[Old Montreal]] | former_names = | postal_code = | addresses = | length_m = | length_ft = | length_mi = | length_km =2 | length_ref = | width = | location =[[Montreal]] | client = | maint = | coordinates = | direction_a =West | terminus_a =Montfort Street | direction_b =East | terminus_b =[[Berri Street]] | junction = | commissioning_date = | construction_start_date = | completion_date = | inauguration_date =1673 | demolition_date = | north = | south = | east = | west = }} [[Image:Bonsecours aglow.jpg|thumb|right|Rue Saint-Paul]] [[Image:DollierRuesMontreal.jpg|thumb|left|[[Montreal]] map drawn by [[François Dollier de Casson]] in 1672]] '''Rue Saint-Paul''' (''Saint Paul Street'') is a street in the [[Old Montreal]] historic area of [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].
The street was laid out by [[François Dollier de Casson]], along the route of a path that had bordered a former fort.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bootsnall.com/namericatravelguides/montreal/apr01mont.shtml |title=A Summer Walk into Montreal's Early Years under French Rule |accessdate=2008-03-02 |last=Goldman |first=Norman |work=Bootsn All Travel}}</ref> Saint Paul is Montreal's oldest street and for many years served as its main thoroughfare.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planetware.com/map-of/montreal-rue-saint-paul-cdn-qu-qumrs.htm |title=Rue Saint Paul |accessdate=2008-03-02 |work=Planetware}}</ref> Paved in 1672, it was named after [[Paul de Chomedey de Maisonneuve]], founder of Montreal, who built a home for himself on it in 1650.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.providenceintl.org/www.providenceintl.org/english/Actuality/PasE/PAS1.html |title=In the footsteps of Emilie |accessdate=2008-03-02 |work=Sisters of Providence |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922042549/http://www.providenceintl.org/www.providenceintl.org/english/Actuality/PasE/PAS1.html |archivedate=September 22, 2008 }}</ref>
The street is home to such landmarks as the [[Bonsecours Market]] and [[Notre-Dame-de-Bon-Secours Chapel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.ville.montreal.qc.ca/archives/democratie/democratie_en/expo/democratisation/revalorisation/piece6/index.shtm |title=Saint Paul Street, Democracy in Montreal |accessdate=2008-03-02 |work=City of Montreal}}</ref> Much of Saint Paul is still paved with [[cobblestones]]. Plans to pedestrianize the street in 2008 were dropped by the [[City of Montreal]] after complaints from merchants.
